article.description: Charlotte Smith-Taylor and Allison Feaster each scored 17 points, leading the Charlotte Sting to a 72-68 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Staley's 10 assists, late FTs pace Charlotte
article.linkText: Sting top Lynx, move into tie for final East spot
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Dawn Staley's biggest contribution came in
the final seconds, and kept the Charlotte Sting's playoff hopes
alive.

Staley finished with 10 assists and seven points, including two
key free throws down the stretch, and teammates Charlotte
Smith-Taylor and Allison Feaster each scored 17 points, leading the
Sting to a 72-68 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Wednesday
night.

The Sting held off a late charge by the Lynx and moved into a
tie for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. At 14-15,
Charlotte is a game out of first place with five games remaining in
the tight Eastern race. The top four teams in each conference
qualify for the playoffs.

"Dawn is so savvy out there, we want the ball in her hands as
much as we can get it," Charlotte coach Trudi Lacey said. "I
wouldn't take anyone else over her at the end."

Staley, fouled with 5.0 seconds on the clock, made both free
throws to put the game out of reach after Minnesota erased a
10-point deficit over the final four minutes, and Smith-Taylor
missed two free throws to keep the Lynx in contention.

Nicole Ohlde led Minnesota with 19 points and eight rebounds,
Svetlana Abrosimova finished with 15 points and Tamika Williams
added 10.

"We let it slip away, and that's the bottom line," Lynx coach
Suzie McConnell Serio said. "We need to be the hungry team. I'm
just disappointed that we didn't come out that way tonight for 40
minutes, because it was there at the beginning."

The Lynx trailed 65-53 with five minutes left and closed within
two points on a fast-break layup by Ohlde with 5.4 seconds
remaining. But Staley converted the free throws to help seal the
win.

The Lynx missed Katie Smith, their leading scorer and top
defender who injured her knee while playing for the U.S. team at
the Athens Olympics last month.

Without Smith's outside shooting, Minnesota hit just 38.7
percent from the field, and without her defensive presence, the
Lynx allowed Charlotte to hit 54.3 percent of its shots.

"You know they miss her when they go 3-for-16 on 3-pointers,"
said Staley, Smith's teammate at the Olympics. "She's an
outstanding scorer and they're missing a lot of points without her.
Sometimes you're going to win without her, but a lot of times,
you're going to take the 'L' without her."

Charlotte used a 10-0 run late in the first half and a 14-3
surge to start the second half to take control, but trailing 65-55
with four minutes left, the Lynx went on a 13-5 burst and cut the
lead to two with 5.4 seconds remaining on Ohlde's fast-break layup.

But Staley took charge, hit her free throws, and left the Lynx
wondering what might have been.

"We haven't lost confidence in this team at all," McConnell
Serio said. "It's there -- you saw the runs we had. We just can't
wait until it's too late to make it happen."
